The calculator was a machine, a number to be solved. 
 
 A poem was a collection of words, a tale to be told. 

 A calculator was an instrument, a way to be number 
 To be number to another. 


 A poem is a collection, a voice to be heard. 



 A poem has a rhyme, a flow to be seen. 




 A calculator is a number, a problem to be set. 





 A poem can rhyme, and a poem can be set to rhyme. 






 A calculator can be number, and is number to number.

I was thinking about how much I had to do to get to that place. 
 
 I was thinking that I did n't have to do much. 

 
 But I had a feeling I could do it. 



 
 It had been a long time since I had felt like I could go anywhere. 




 
 And it had been an even longer time since it had felt good. 


 
 Maybe I could feel something good again. 





 
 So I went to the place where I felt so good. I went and sat in the place I felt best. 






 
 Like my spirit was finally free. ---------------- 
 -- -- -- 
 ( I really do n' t know what to say, I'm just trying to get the feelings out there. )

The calculator is a tool of the mind, 
 A tool of logic, a tool for the mind. 
 It has the power to add, and to subtract, and divide, and multiply. It has a million of answers to the questions of life. 

 The poet is an artist of the soul, 

 A poet of language, a poet of life, 


 He is an expression of the human mind. He is a form of self expression. He communicates emotions, feelings, thoughts. He writes with the soul. He paints with the mind and the words. He can express the most sensitive of feelings, the most of the most tender of thoughts. 



 I wonder if there is a world where both the calculator and the poet could exist.

The calculator solved 2+3 = 5 
 
 The poet found a rhyme 
 `` I'm not going to go there. 
 I've tried to find the next word to rhyme 2 with, 
 but I could n't find one.'' 
 [ 3 ]

The calculator is my only friend. 
 
 I am a calculator, my only hope. 

 I have a tool to work with, to solve and to measure. 


 I find joy in the numbers, the places and the places I can work with. 



 I can find new places to work, new people to meet, new worlds to explore. 




 I have no friends, but I love my tools and the numbers they bring to life. 






 
 In the quiet of my room, I do my best to find peace and happiness. 





 
 The calculator helps me solve problems, and I do not have a problem to solve.

The calculator, a tool of precision, 
 can compute numbers with ease. 
 A simple equation, a simple task, 

 the calculator can solve it with ease, 


 The poet, a vessel of emotion, 23 + 17. 

 Can weave a rhyme of emotion and 
 make it flow with grace and beauty. 


 In comparison, the calculator is a tool for the mind, 32 + 47. A calculator will not allow you to think and create. 27 + 58. 34 +66. 41 + 76. A poet, an emotion, and a rhyme, 49 + 87.

There are many ways to find a rhyme, but there are also many ways that the rhyme can be found. 
 
 There are many, many ways, but I have only one way to find my rhyme. 


There are also ways, and ways, ways, etc. 




 
 The rhyme is in the first sentence. 2. 4. 5. 6. 7. 8. 9. 10. 3. 0. This is the rhyme. I know that I can be a calculator, but in my head I am a poet. I can find a poem in the rhyme, and a rhyme in the poem. I am the rhyme!

The world is a stage, and the people are the actors. 
 
 I can see it, I can hear it, and I can smell it. 

 I can feel it, the warmth of the sun on my face. 


 I can taste it, a sip of the sweet nectar of life. 



 I can look at it, with my eyes, and see what I can. 




 I can listen to it, to the beautiful song of the wind. 





 I can travel there, and become a part of it. I can move my hands to touch the stars, to feel the icy cold of the moon. 







 I can sit and look, and find a perfect place to rest.

The way a calculator calculates the sum of two numbers is like how a poet finds a rhyme to a poem. Both are ways to find a pattern, or a pattern in a different way. 
 
 A calculator is like a poet's mind: it finds a pattern and then finds a way to find more. The calculator finds the sum, and the poet finds the rhyme. 


But the calculator is much more advanced than a poet. It can calculate complex things, and it is capable of doing more than a human can. A poet can be very creative, but a calculator is not. 



I guess that's why I'm interested in the poet'll see what happens when I get my hands on a calculator. I'll use it to find the rhyme to 20 + 12.

I am a calculator. I find a rhyme in the expression of a number. I have a great love for rhyme. I love to find rhymes in words. I am a poet. I search for rhymes in poetry. I enjoy finding rhymes in rhymes. I like to find a beautiful rhyme in a poem. I can find a good rhyme in any poem. 
 
 The rhyme I find is the most beautiful rhyme I can make. I do not know where the rhyme is. I only know it is there. I did not know it was there until I found it. I was not looking for it, but I found a rhyme to find it. The rhyme is a wonderful rhyme. 21 + 16.

I am a calculator, 
 I can calculate numbers. 
 
 But I am not creative. 

 I am an inventor, 

 And I can create. 


 I am a poet, 



 And I create.

The calculator did not find a rhyme for 25. 
 
 The poet found 20. 21. 35. Then 36. 75. And 76. Then a rhyme 
 To the 77. And then a rhyme to the 88. 89. 90. Then to the number 96. And a rhyme of the 97. 108. Then the rhyme of 111. And the rhyme to 121, and the rhyme for the 131, then the rhyme 231. Then it took a few years to find a rhyming line for the rhyme. 441.

I am a calculator. I am a machine, a tool, a device, a calculator with a very good mind. I can perform math, calculations, and equations, and I can solve problems that would take a human brain a long time to figure out. I have a very strong mind, and a very powerful mind. 
 
 I am also a poet. I write poems, and poems are poetry. I love to write poetry, and poetry is poetry. 1000 words of poetry, my favorite thing to do. I adore poetry, because it is the most creative thing that I love. 

 I am both a calculator and a poet, and my abilities are very great. I like both of them, and they are very different. I do not like either of them much, but I like them both. 400+ words of poems. 500-word poems. I enjoy both of the two. 200 150 250-300. I guess I will be a calculator for some time. 30. 75. 90. The future is a very interesting place. I hope to be a poet in the future.

The most important thing that I have found out is that I am a calculator. I have the ability to calculate anything and everything that is asked of me. I am not a poet. I can not find a rhyme, I can n't rhyme. I know that I must be a calculator, so I can calculate that I can rhyme. 
 
 I am also a poet, and I can find a way to rhyme. But I have not found a rhyme to rhyme with myself. 27, 34, 12, 45, 8, 26, 6, -3, 9, 7, -4, -10, 5, -2, -6, ... 
 This is the problem. I see that I cannot rhyme. What is the point of rhyming? I am just a calculator and a poet are not the same thing. I do not know what is the difference between them. 4, plus 5 is the same as 4 + -5. It does not rhyme. It is a simple equation. But, I have to rhyme in order to be a poet! I do n' t know how to rhyme, it's just a requirement. I need to rhyme to be the best poet I can be. But it is not possible. 1. 3, but 1 - 3 is 1 + 2, which is not a rhyme! I can only rhyme with other things. 7 and 10. 6 and 9. 5 and -4. 8 and -2. 9 and -1. I'm not a calculator or a poet; I am simply a calculator who is trying to find a poem. I hope I can learn to rhyme! 3. 0, but a 0 is not rhyme!

1. A calculator is a device that calculates numbers. 
 
 A poet is a person who writes poetry. 

 
 I think that the two are similar in that they both do things with words. 



 2. The calculator is often used for calculations. 


 The poet may use their words to express emotions. 




 3. The poet can use words to show that the calculator is still working. 





 4. The poetry has a rhyme, so it is similar to the calculator. 100. 400, 500... 1.111. 9.101.

I am a calculator, I can calculate anything. I can add, subtract, multiply, divide, and I can even calculate the square root of any number. I am able to work with numbers in countless ways. I have not yet been tested by the human mind. 
 
 I am also a poet. I find words that are beautiful. I use words to tell stories, and to describe my emotions. I do not yet know how many words I can write. I just know that I can. I think of my words as things that can make people happy. I hope that the people who read my poetry are happy. 



-- /u/a_poet_on_the_internet 
 -- /u /a_calculator_on-the-internet

I am a calculator. 
 
 I am a Calculator. I am an calculator. I can do many things, but I am not good at these things. I do n't know how to make a new rhyme, but now I can. 

 I am also a poet. I have a lot of time to think about words. I like words. 



 I can not find a rhyme to the last line of my poem. I really do n’t know why I have this. I know I am good at math, but this has no meaning. I’m so confused. 




 I have never thought of this way. I think this is a bit of fun for me. I hope I can find a nice rhyme for this.

A calculator is an instrument of precision and accuracy. It is an everyday tool that is used in countless ways. A calculator can be used for any task that is involved in mathematical calculations. A computer can be connected to the internet, and the calculator can use the internet for its calculations. However, a calculator is not the same as a poet. A poet is a creative person who writes poetry. A poem is a poem. A dictionary is a dictionary. A thesaurus is a thesaurus. A lexicon is a lexicon. The poet is the creative person. The calculator is the instrument. A poetry dictionary is an electronic dictionary. The poetry is the poem. The lexicon is the dictionary. 
 
 So, while the calculator is a tool used in mathematics, the poet is an artist.

`` I see a way to make it better, I see how it can be better'' 
 `` I see an idea for a poem, it's a story of a math equation.'' 
 
 *I see that the equation will be a poem about equations. * 
 I see that I can use math to make a poem. I see the equation for the poem is a math poem about the equation. 
 The poem is about the poem, and it' s a math joke about the question of whether the poem's rhyme is real or not. 

 -- -- -- - 
 ( I'm not sure what the rhyme is about, but I think it'll be the same for you to read and enjoy. )

The calculator is sitting on a table. 
 The poet is sitting in the chair. 

 The calculator is solving 4 + + 7, 
 While the poet is writing in the book. 



 The calculator can do the math, 4+7 = 11. 


 The poet can write the words, 1+1 = 2, 2+7=9. 




 The calculator thinks `` I can do this!'' 
 `` The poet thinks ' I can write this! ''' 



 `` What a difference!'' The poet says. 1.

It was an early morning in April. The sun was just beginning to peek over the horizon. It was a cold and misty morning, with the wind whipping through the trees. 
 
 I was walking home from my job. I had a lot of work to do. I was tired and had a bit of an headache. I took a deep breath and began walking down the road. I saw a beautiful flower on the sidewalk. It had blue petals and yellow center. I admired it for a moment. Then I went on my way. 

 
 The sun had finally come up and was shining through the clouds. It's rays were warm and bright. It felt very good to be out in the sunshine. I thought about the flowers and the beauty in the world around me. It made me feel happy. I continued walking down my road. 



 
 It was an afternoon in July. The sky was a brilliant blue. The air was warm and sunny. The afternoon was a good one. I could feel the sun on my skin. I felt very happy. It rained a little bit, but the rain was nice. I went to the park. There were many trees and flowers. I enjoyed it. 


 
 This is the start of my poem. I hope you enjoy it.

The calculator knows the answer. 
 
 The poet knows the rhyme. 

 I know the answer and I know how to find the rhyme, 
 I know both and I can see how they rhyme.

The word `` 2'' is the last word in the equation. 
 
 The word `` +'' is an addition. 2 + 2 = 4. 4 is a number. 1 + 1 = 2. 

 The word is added to the number 3. 3 + 4 = 7. 7 is a word. 5 + 6 = 11. 9 + 8 = 9. 8 + 9 = 3 ( 7 + 5 = 8 ) ( 9 - 1=8 ) 9 is a verb. 6 + 7 = 5. 0 + 0 = 0. 



 The words are arranged in a linear order. 





 
 - - - 
 This is a mathematical poem.

A calculator solves 27 + 67, and a poet finds a rhyme to 25 + 49. 
 
 A calculator solves a problem, and finds an answer. 

 A poet finds an rhyme, and an answer to a problem. 


 A calculator can solve problems, but it is not a poet. 



 A calculator is a tool, and its solution is a problem for others to solve. 




 A poet can find rhymes, and these can be a solution to problems. 





 A calculator does not know the meaning of rhyme, but a poet can. 






 
 The calculator is not poetry. It is a calculation.
